%N A395465 Decimal expansion of the area of the constructible squarable lune whose circular arcs have central angles in a 3:1 ratio and common chord of unit length.
%C A395465 One of the five constructible squarable lunes. It was discovered by Hippocrates of Chios in the 5th century BC.
%C A395465 Called the "isosceles trapezoid lune" by Shelburne (2005).
%C A395465 A lune is a crescent-shaped plane figure bounded by two circular arcs of unequal radii.
%C A395465 A squarable lune is one that can be squared, i.e., a square with an identical area can be constructed using only a compass and a straightedge.
%C A395465 Chebotarev (1935) and Dorodnov (1947) proved that there are precisely five squarable lunes that are also constructible, i.e., can be constructed with a compass and a straightedge.
%C A395465 For a squarable lune the central angles of its two arcs must be commensurable, i.e., their ratio must be a rational number, or equivalently, they are integral multiples of a common angle.
%C A395465 Following the notation in Postnikov (2000), let the central angles of the two arcs be 2*alpha and 2*beta. There exist positive integers k and m (k > m) such that alpha = k * theta and beta = m * theta.
%C A395465 A lune is squarable if it satisfies the condition sin(k*theta)^2/k = sin(m*theta)^2/m, and it is constructible if the angle theta is constructible.
%C A395465 By inscribing a polygonal chain of k equal segments in the outer arc and m equal segments in the inner arc, a resulting (k+m)-sided polygon is formed, and its area is equal to the area of the lune.
%C A395465 Assuming the common chord of the arcs is of unit length, the radii of the two arcs are 1/(2*sin(alpha)) and 1/(2*sin(beta)). The area of the lune is given by alpha/sin(alpha)^2 - beta/sin(beta)^2 + cot(betha)/4 - cot(alpha)/4.
%C A395465 The five lunes are often characterized in literature by the ratio of their central angles or by the shape of the polygon with the same area. The first lune, corresponding to the 2:1 ratio, is known as the Lune of Hippocrates.
%C A395465   k | m | theta              | area               | polygon
%C A395465   --+------------------------+------------------- +--------------------------
%C A395465   2 | 1 | 0.785... (A003881) | 0.25     (A020773) | isosceles right triangle
%C A395465   3 | 1 | 0.598... (A395469) | 0.423... (A395465) | isosceles trapezoid
%C A395465   3 | 2 | 0.467... (A395470) | 0.142... (A395466) | concave pentagon
%C A395465   5 | 1 | 0.409... (A395471) | 0.705... (A395467) | hexagon
%C A395465   5 | 3 | 0.293... (A395472) | 0.180... (A395468) | concave octagon
